com: What is the bare minimum I need to put together a home studio to make psych rock/pop music?
last_replies:
[{'no': 114023049, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)00:06:35', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>114022871
not really an expert on gear stuff so i dunno lol. i've had both a P-Bass and a Jazz Bass, and i prefer the P-bass out of the two. if you've got any favorite bassists in particular you could always check Equipboard and see what their setups are like', 'time': 1670907995, 'resto': 114022559}, {'no': 114023247, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)00:23:13', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>114023049
Thanks anon I'll do some research. I've always liked the look of mustang bases though', 'time': 1670908993, 'resto': 114022559}, {'no': 114026641, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)05:30:08', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>114022559
barest minimum
>guitar with some humbuckers (heavy rhythm), and guitar with singles (if you have a multi-pickup setup, this works too)
>bass, specifically one with a Humbucker or split coil. (if you want a heavier bass tone, get a short-scale)
>computer with a DAW. (logic, pro tools, ableton are some of the better ones for live instruments. if you cant afford, garageband is free)
>audio interface to plug guitars into computer
>some sort of amp modeling software (i use Bias FX, but you can go really far with just stock plugins and amp modelers)
>microphone for vocals. (SM58 is fine, or you can splurge for a more "studio quality" microphone)
the only tricky part is drums. live drums would be best for the genre if you go super traditional sounding psych rock. if not you can use loops or drum machines for a newer and more experimental sound. whatever sounds good sounds good. have fun!', 'time': 1670927408, 'resto': 114022559}, {'no': 114026655, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)05:32:05', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>114026641
adding onto this, i forgot to mention you could always do DAWless and go with the pedal board, reel-to-reel, analog synths, the whole nine yards, but that's going to be MUCH more expensive and less intuitive than digital, and might even be more limiting considering some of the "out-there" tones and soundscapes we can achieve nowadays with computers.', 'time': 1670927525, 'resto': 114022559}, {'no': 114027226, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)06:34:55', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'I wouldn't focus too much on what exact gear is traditionally used for the genre you want to make. For example, instead of using a bass you could pitch down a (palm muted) guitar or use a synth bass (although I do admit that short scale basses sound pretty awesome). for drums you could use samples/drum machines, etc.
These sort of limitations can really help you create your own sound.
Of course there's nothing wrong with using the "real" instruments, especially if it makes you play with other people.
The same philosophy applies to recording techniques, etc.', 'time': 1670931295, 'resto': 114022559}]

I'm becoming basic and it's honestly really nice not having to eat 100 albums to find 1 or 2 that I like, or having shared interests with normal people, or not feeling like a snob music nerd.

I recommend it.
